2026-04-21 01:34:29 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 3 (internal through‑series path on positive line)'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that up to CM2 the series path is intact: CM1 and CM2 each have ≈12 V between their inputs and outputs with switches ON, and continuity from input (+/−) to output (+/−) is good. \n\nAt CM3, however, the input sees ≈12 V on (+) and 0 V on (−), but both output terminals are at 0 V when the chain is assembled and energized. When tested with the connector open and battery removed, continuity of the cables themselves is nominal, but the diagnostic notes that the negative port (‘n’) of the input (+) cable is floating/disconnected from the circuit. This indicates an internal open fault in CM3’s internal through‑series path on the positive side (likely at or near the junction from the input(+) terminal to the internal switch/through track). As a result, +12 V cannot propagate beyond CM3, so CM4 and all later modules—including the load—see 0 V. \n\nThus, the root cause is an internal open circuit in Control Module 3’s positive through‑series path. Replacing or repairing Control Module 3 (its internal positive line from input to output) should restore power to the downstream modules and allow the lamp to operate when all switches are ON.'
